Waimea Waves

Noah Salas

March 30, 2018


Part 1


Framing the problem

  • Objective: Hold WSL contest where, through the duration of the contest, the waves are at least 3 meters tall.
  • Strongs Task: Help WSL forecast wave heights at Waimea Bay so they can meet their objective.

Questions:

Forecasts should be made at intersection of statistical confidence and business use

  • Length of contest? 1 day vs 3-4 days?
  • Latest date a forecast is useful to you? 1 year, 6 months, 1 month?
  • Such thing as too all of waves? (safety)
  • Any reason to believe your current data has bias/measurement error?
  • Seasonal/Business contraints? (travel/accommodation/tourism)
  • Delivery of results and timing


Data Enrichment

  • Additional wave height data (Jason 3 satellite)
  • Wind speed / direction - affects waves (Wunderground)
  • Precipitation - quality of competition and viewing (Wunderground)
  • Historical travel/accommodation use and costs

Approaches

The data youve acquired for Strong to use is time related. Time related statistical analysis require certain considerations since a time series of wave height, for instance, is correlated with functions of itself.

Despite this, time series of interest (\(y_t\)) can sometimes be broken out into components. This can help us better understand them and forecast. These components are:

\[y_t = T_t + S_t + R_t\]

  • Trend (\(T_t\)): Long-term increases or decreases in the data.
  • Seasonal (\(S_t\)): A seasonal pattern in the data (yearly , monthly, etc.). This component is always fixed and has a known period.
  • Remainder (\(R_t\)): Data variation that cant be accounted for by the other components. Should be random.

Here is a visual example:

plot(decompose(co2))

If we see something like this (which I suspect we will), it might be possible to get accurate forecasts with easy to understand methods such as moving averages or past (lagged) versions of our time series. So this is where I will start.

So it looks like most of these features (and their lags) are highly correlated with the Waimea Bay wave height (and its lags). So for now Im going to move forward focusing on the wave height series to better understand and deconstruct it.

Missingness

As mentioned earlier we can handle missingness a few ways. I would think that we could use another series to inform us on what the missing Waimea Bay wave heights should be. For instance:

plot(X$wave_height_51201h,X$wave_height_51101h, xlab = "Waimea Bay Wave height (m)", ylab = "NW Hawaii 2 Wave height (m)")

But then again maybe the series itself would be more informative on how to impute, like a simple linear interpolation. Lets test this:

  • I randomly select 1 of 2 sub-series of our NW Hawaii 2 and Waimea Bay wave height series where theres no missing values.
  • I randomly assign 25% of the samples in these sub-series to be holdout data, the rest I use to train with
  • I run three methods on the training data:
    • Regress Waimea Bay wave height on NW Hawaii 2 wave height
    • Regress Waimea Bay wave height on NW Hawaii 2 wave height with AR(1) error term
    • Linearly interpolate Waimea Bay wave height
  • Once I have these models, I evaluate them against the holdout set, and generate a RMSE
  • Repeat \(n\) times
#missingness
set.seed(1234)
train_prop = .75
n = 1000
m = c("linear regression", "linear regression AR(1)", "linear interpolation")
k = length(m)
miss_mat <- matrix(data=NA, nrow=n, ncol=k)
for(i in 1:n){
  
  if(runif(1) >= 0.5){
    Xmiss <- X[X$date >= "2010-03-01" & X$date <= "2012-01-01",]
  } else {
    Xmiss <- X[X$date >= "2015-05-01" & X$date <= "2016-11-01",]
  }
  
  train <- sample.int(n = nrow(Xmiss), size = floor(train_prop*nrow(Xmiss)), replace = FALSE)
  ys <- Xmiss$wave_height_51201h[-train]
  
  miss_mod_lm <- arima(Xmiss$wave_height_51201h[train], order = c(0,0,0) , xreg=Xmiss$wave_height_51101h[train])
  preds <- predict(miss_mod_lm, newxreg= Xmiss$wave_height_51101h[-train])$pred
  
  miss_mod_ar <- arima(Xmiss$wave_height_51201h[train], order = c(1,0,0) , xreg=Xmiss$wave_height_51101h[train])
  preds2 <- predict(miss_mod_ar , newxreg= Xmiss$wave_height_51101h[-train])$pred
  
  Xmiss$wave_height_51201h[-train] <- NA
  preds3 <- zoo::na.approx(Xmiss$wave_height_51201h, rule = 2)[-train]
  miss_mat[i,] <- c(sqrt(mean((preds - ys)^2)),
                    sqrt(mean((preds2 - ys)^2)),
                    sqrt(mean((preds3 - ys)^2)))
}
colnames(miss_mat) <- m
miss_plt <- melt(miss_mat[,1:3])[,2:3]
colnames(miss_plt) <- c("method","RMSE")
ggplot(miss_plt, aes(RMSE, fill = method)) + geom_density(alpha = 0.25)

It appears the three methods perform similarly on how well they impute missing values, so to keep things simple I will impute my Waimea Bay wave hieghts using linear interpolation

Decisions

  1. Use Waimea Bay wave height as target (dependent) variable.
  2. Keep data at daily level
  3. Missingness handled by using linear interpolation imputation


2. Variance


If we look more closely, at the Waimea Bay wave height series, it looks like the variance is not constant across the series (more spread at the spikes). Lets investigate:

wave_height_wb <- ts(zoo::na.approx(X$wave_height_51201h),start = c(2010,1),frequency = 365)
month_var <- X %>% group_by(year(X$date),month(X$date)) %>% summarise(variance = var(wave_height_51201h, na.rm = TRUE))
month_var$time <- 1:dim(month_var)[1]
plot(month_var$time,month_var$variance,type="b", xlab = "Month", ylab = "Variance")

This is an issue, the series needs to have constant variance over time so any model results are interpretable. We can use a Box-Cox transformation to help achieve this:

\[ w_t = \frac{y_t^{\lambda} - 1}{\lambda} \]

We choose a lambda that will minimize the variation in this seasonal series:

l <- BoxCox.lambda(wave_height_wb)
wave_height_wb_bc <- BoxCox(wave_height_wb,l)
print(l)
[1] -0.7583262
month_var <- X %>% group_by(year(X$date),month(X$date)) %>% summarise(variance = var(BoxCox(wave_height_51201h,l), na.rm = TRUE))
month_var$time <- 1:dim(month_var)[1]
plot(month_var$time,month_var$variance, type="b", xlab = "Month", ylab = "Variance")

plot(wave_height_wb_bc)

This transformed series now has a more constant variance.

Decisions

  1. Use Box-Cox transformation to make variance more constant


3. Stationarity


So lets decompose our transformed series to see what we find. We will do this by first determining the trend component using a moving average. We remove it, then compute the seasonal component by averaging, for each time unit, over all periods. We then remove the seasonal component and the remainder is whats left.

d2 <- decompose(wave_height_wb_bc, type = "additive")
plot(decompose(wave_height_wb_bc))

As expected, more evidence of a yearly seasonal component. The trend component contributes very little to the overall series variablity:

rbind(c("trend","seasonal","random"),
      c(var(d2$trend,na.rm = TRUE),var(d2$seasonal,na.rm = TRUE),var(d2$random,na.rm = TRUE)) / var(d2$x))
     [,1]                 [,2]                [,3]               
[1,] "trend"              "seasonal"          "random"           
[2,] "0.0145321495537638" "0.487267295705825" "0.468336627918005"

To finish making this series stationary, we need take this seasonal component into account. We can do this by differencing.

dif <- diff(wave_height_wb_bc,365)
plot(dif)

Decisions

  1. Use seasonal differencing


4. ACF and PACF plots


Autocorrelation function (ACF) plots the coefficients of correlation between a time series and lags of itself. The partial autocorrelation function (PACF) plots the partial coefficients of correlation between a time series and lags of itself. Partial autocorrelation is the amount of correlation between a variable and a lag of itself that is not explained by correlations at all lower order lags.

Why do we care? These measures can help us identify the numbers of AR and/or MA terms that would be relevant to use in modeling

acf(dif, lag.max = 365.25*5)

pacf(dif, lag.max = 365.25*5)

The spikes and then tapering off of the spikes seasonally (just after each integer label) indicate a non-seasonal AR(1) and MA(1) term might be useful in the model.

Decisions

  1. AR(1) and MA(1) terms seem useful to initiallizing modeling process


5. Modeling


So the first model Ill fit looks like this:

\[ w_t^{'} = \phi_1 w_{t-1}^{'} + \theta_1 e_{t-1} + e_t \] , where \(w_t^{'}\) is the transformed and seasonally differenced Waimea Bay wave height time series.

fit1 <- Arima(wave_height_wb,
      order = c(1,0,1),
      seasonal = c(0,1,0),
      lambda = l)

Lets forecast a year out:

f1 <- forecast(fit1,h=365)
plot(f1)
lines(f1$lower[,2], col="blue", lty="dashed")
lines(f1$upper[,2], col="blue", lty="dashed")

While these forecasts seem logical, they are not seasonally smooth and vary considerably. This is because of the seasonal (365 day) differencing.

A recommended alternative approach is to use Fourier transforms to model the seasonal pattern, while still using AR and/or MA terms for the error portion to handle short term dynamics. The Fourier terms consist of sine/cosine waves of different amplitudes and frequencies that allow the model to capture cycles of certain periods that may be present in the series. This would look something like this:

\[ w_t = a + \sum_{k=1}^{K}\left( \alpha_k sin(\frac{2 \pi k t}{m}) + \beta_k cos(\frac{2 \pi k t}{m}) \right) + N_t \] , where \(w_t\) is the transformed Waimea Bay wave height time series, \(m\) is the length of the series, and \(N_t = \phi_1 w_{t-1} + \theta_1 e_{t-1} + e_t\) are ARMA errors.

\(K\) controls how many Fourier terms there are and can be tuned. The larger the \(K\), the more wiggly the seasonal pattern can become.

fit_fourier_aicc <- vector()
for(i in 1:16){
  fittemp <- Arima(wave_height_wb, order=c(1,0,1), xreg=fourier(wave_height_wb, K=i), lambda=l)
  fit_fourier_aicc[i] <- fittemp$aicc
}
which.min(fit_fourier_aicc)
[1] 4

So lets use this \(K\):

fitf <- Arima(wave_height_wb, order=c(1,0,1), xreg=fourier(wave_height_wb, K=which.min(fit_fourier_aicc)), lambda=l)

Cross Validation


Before we move onto forecasting, lets pressure test this model a bit more. We can do this using a time series style cross validation- take different ordinal slices of training and test data and generate an accuracy measure on each test set. It look like this (5 folds, black is training data, red is test data):

par(mfrow = c(3,2))
k <- round(length(wave_height_wb)/365) - 3
base <- 365*2
a1 <- c(NA,NA,NA,NA,NA)
aa <- c(NA,NA,NA,NA,NA)
for(i in 1:k){
  train_end <- base + (i*365)
  test_start <- train_end + 1
  test_end <- test_start + 364
  
  train <- wave_height_wb[1:train_end]
  test <- wave_height_wb[test_start:test_end]
  
  plot(train, xlim = c(1,length(wave_height_wb)), type="l" , ylab = "Wave Height", xlab = "Days")
  lines(test_start:test_end,test,col="red")
  
}

Lets compare my model to a basline of auto.arima() which attempts to automate model steps 3-5. The hope is my models cross validation error is less than those of a plug-n-play option:

k <- round(length(wave_height_wb)/365) - 3
base <- 365*2
my_acc <- c(NA,NA,NA,NA,NA)
auto_acc <- c(NA,NA,NA,NA,NA)
for(i in 1:k){
  train_end <- base + (i*365)
  test_start <- train_end + 1
  test_end <- test_start + 364
  
  train <- ts(wave_height_wb[1:train_end],frequency = 365)
  test <- wave_height_wb[test_start:test_end]
  
  moda <- auto.arima(train,lambda = l)
  predsa <- forecast(moda,h=365)$mean
  a <- accuracy(f=predsa,x=test)
  auto_acc <- rbind(auto_acc,a)
  
  mod1 <- Arima(train, order=c(1,0,1), xreg=fourier(train, K=which.min(fit_fourier_aicc)), lambda=l)
  preds1 <- forecast(mod1, h=365, xreg=fourier(train, K=which.min(fit_fourier_aicc), h=365))$mean
  a <- accuracy(f=preds1,x=test)
  my_acc <- rbind(my_acc,a)
  
  #plot(forecast(mod1,h=365))
  #plot(forecast(moda, h=365, xreg=fourier(train, K=which.min(fit_fourier_aicc), h=365)))
  
}
#my_acc[-1,]

Decisions

  1. I settled on a model with Fourier transforms to handle seasonal dynamics and AR(1) / MA(1) errors to handle short term dynamics.
  2. I validated this approach using a 5-fold cross validation.

Next Steps


Ive been keeping track of important decisions Ive made on this short modeling path, with the view of using alternatives of these as potential next steps / exploration. Lets update this list a bit and describe some things I would investigate:

  • Investigate the use of other features, both the ones already provided and new ones (particularly wind data)
    • Sensitivity around other buoys as part of target signal
    • Incorporate other covariates
  • More thorough valuation of missing data imputation
  • Investigate possibility / effectiveness of more than 1 seasonal pattern
  • Model using other methods:
    • Exponential smoothing
    • Neural nets
    • Stack them?
  • More extensive cross-validation routine
